'Though my crisis has reached a successful end here, unfortunately the Ebola crisis continues to spin out of control in West Africa,' Sacra said. 

Sacra has worked in Liberia for much of his career, living there between 1995 and 2010. He said he considers it his second home and the 'odds I'll end up back (in Liberia) are pretty high.'

Debbie Sacra spent most of the news conference watching her husband of 29 years instead of the room full of reporters and hospital workers. Their three sons also attended. 

The two shared their first hug in nearly two months Thursday morning.

'I think this is the longest we’ve been apart in 29 years of marriage,' she said. 

Two other American aid workers who contracted Ebola — including Brantly — were treated at Emory University Hospital in Atlanta, and were released after recovering. A fourth American with Ebola is still being treated in Atlanta.

